<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-09-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-09-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="524" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d524">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Frederick W. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr. Pruyn</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 75.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-09-24"><hi rend="italic">September</hi> 24, 1864.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your despatch of May 30, No. 39, has been
                            received, and your proceedings in regard to the opening of the inland
                            sea are approved.</p>
                        <p>You are still at liberty to modify your action so far as your judgment
                            may dictate, concurrently with the representatives of the western
                            powers.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>FREDERICK W. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Robert H. Pruyn</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c.,&amp;c., Kanagawa.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>